On June 23, 2010, the Diamondbacks announced that the team would retire its first jersey number by honoring [[Luis Gonzalez (outfielder)|Luis Gonzalez]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://arizona.diamondbacks.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100623&amp;content_id=11516306&amp;vkey=news_ari&amp;fext=.jsp&amp;c_id=ari=2010-06-27|date=June 23, 2010|title=D'Backs to retire Gonzo's number Aug. 7|author=Pentis, Andrew|work=MLB.com}}&lt;/ref&gt; Gonzalez played with the Diamondbacks for eight seasons, 1999 to 2006, and attended five All-Star games representing the team. His number, #20, was retired in a pre-game ceremony which was held at Chase Field on August 7, 2010 in front of a sellout crowd of 48,946.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://arizona.sbnation.com/2010/6/23/1533684/diamondbacks-to-honor-luis|accessdate=June 24, 2010|date=June 23, 2010|title=Diamondbacks To Honor Luis Gonzalez, Retire No. 20|author=Williams, Cory|work=SBNation Arizona}}&lt;/ref&gt; After the ceremony, the Diamondbacks won the game against the [[San Diego Padres]] 6–5 after a walk-off home run by [[Chris Young (outfielder)|Chris Young]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iVEAO4h_XK-M7MC0VwqSUCVjb97gD9HF2H8O2 The Associated Press: Young's bookend homers lead D'Backs to 6–5 win]{{dead link|date=September 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

