'''Aaliyah Dana Haughton''' (January 16, 1979 &amp;ndash; August 25, 2001), who performed under the [[mononymous person|mononym]] '''Aaliyah''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|ə|ˈ|l|iː|ə}}), was an American recording artist, actress and model. She was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York, and was raised in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]. At an early age, she appeared on the television show ''[[Star Search]]'' and performed in concert alongside [[Gladys Knight]]. At age 12, Aaliyah signed with [[Jive Records]] and her uncle [[Barry Hankerson]]'s [[Blackground Records]]. Hankerson introduced her to [[R. Kelly]], who became her mentor, as well as lead songwriter and producer of her debut album, ''[[Age Ain't Nothing but a Number]]''. The album sold three million copies in the United States and was certified double platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). After facing allegations of an illegal marriage with Kelly, Aaliyah ended her contract with Jive and signed with [[Atlantic Records]].

Aaliyah worked with record producers [[Timbaland]] and [[Missy Elliott]] for her second album,  ''[[One in a Million (Aaliyah album)|One in a Million]]''; it sold 3.7 million copies in the United States and over eight million copies worldwide. In 2000, Aaliyah appeared in her first major film, ''[[Romeo Must Die]]''. She contributed to the film's soundtrack, which spawned the single &quot;[[Try Again]]&quot;. The song topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] solely on [[airplay]], making Aaliyah the first artist in ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' history to achieve this feat. &quot;Try Again&quot; earned Aaliyah a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for Best Female R&amp;B Vocalist.

After completing ''Romeo Must Die'', Aaliyah filmed her part in ''[[Queen of the Damned (film)|Queen of the Damned]]''. She released her third and final album, ''[[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]'', in July 2001. On August 25, 2001, Aaliyah and eight others were killed in an airplane crash in [[The Bahamas]] after filming the [[music video]] for the single &quot;[[Rock the Boat (Aaliyah song)|Rock the Boat]]&quot;. The [[aviator|pilot]], Luis Morales III, was unlicensed at the time of the accident and had traces of [[cocaine]] and [[alcohol]] in his system. Aaliyah's family later filed a [[wrongful death claim|wrongful death]] lawsuit against [[Blackhawk International Airways]], which was settled out of court. Since then, Aaliyah's music has continued to achieve commercial success with several posthumous releases. Aaliyah recorded several number one [[R&amp;B]] hits and five top ten [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] singles. She has been credited for helping redefine [[Contemporary R&amp;B|R&amp;B]] and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], earning her the nickname &quot;[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Princess of R&amp;B]]&quot;. She is listed by ''Billboard'' as the tenth most successful female R&amp;B artist of the past 25 years, and 27th most successful R&amp;B artist overall.&lt;ref name=&quot;Billboard&quot;&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/column/the-juice/the-top-50-r-b-hip-hop-artists-of-the-past-1004127916.story#/column/the-juice/the-top-50-r-b-hip-hop-artists-of-the-past-1004127916.story|title=The Top 50 R&amp;B / Hip-Hop Artists of the Past 25 Years|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|last2=Caulfield| first2=Keith|last3=Ramirez|first3=Rauly| date= November 18, 2010|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=April 4, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Early life==
Aaliyah Dana Haughton was born on January 16, 1979, in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Allmusic&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p44722|pure_url=yes}}|title=Aaliyah &gt; Biography|last=Huey|first=Steve|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=November 8, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; Born of predominantly [[African American]] descent,&lt;ref name=&quot;CNN&quot;&gt;{{cite news|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/COMMUNITY/08/27/welbekin.cnna/index.html|title=Vibe Magazine's Emil Wilbekin: Remembering Aaliyah|date=August 27, 2001|publisher=CNN|accessdate=May 6, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; with some [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] ancestry from her grandmother,&lt;ref name=s1&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=1|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; she was the second and younger child of Diane and Michael Haughton.&lt;ref name=s1/&gt; At a young age, Aaliyah was enrolled in voice lessons by her mother,&lt;ref name=&quot;Allmusic&quot;/&gt; and she would perform at weddings, [[church choir]] and charity events.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=9|Ref=Sutherland}}&lt;/ref&gt; When she was five years old, her family moved to [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], where she was raised along with her older brother, Rashad.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Kenyatta|2002|p=3|Ref=Kenyatta}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;AMG rock&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last=Bogdanov|first=Vladimir|coauthors=Woodstra, Chris; Erlewine, Stephen Thomas|title=All Music Guide to Rock|publisher=[[Hal Leonard Corporation]]|year=2002|page=1|isbn=0-87930-653-X}}&lt;/ref&gt; She attended a Catholic school, Gesu Elementary, where she received a part in the stage play ''[[Annie (musical)|Annie]]'' in [[first grade]]. From then on, she was determined to become an entertainer.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Farley|2002|p=23|Ref=Farley}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah's mother was a vocalist, and her uncle, [[Barry Hankerson]], was an [[entertainment law]]yer who had been married to [[Gladys Knight]].&lt;ref name=&quot;AMG rock&quot;/&gt; As a child, Aaliyah traveled with Knight and worked with an agent in New York to audition for commercials and [[television program]]s, including ''[[Family Matters]]''; she went on to appear on ''[[Star Search]]'' at the age of nine.&lt;ref name=&quot;Allmusic&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=15|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; She then auditioned for several record labels and appeared in concerts alongside Knight at age 11.&lt;ref name=&quot;AMG rock&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/aaliyah-755377.html|title=Aaliyah – Obituaries, News|last=Perrone|first=Pierre|date=August 27, 2001|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News &amp; Media]]|accessdate=April 4, 2009 | location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Career==
===1991–95: ''Age Ain't Nothing but a Number''===
After Hankerson signed a distribution deal with [[Jive Records]], he signed Aaliyah to his [[Blackground Records]] label at the age of 12.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Farley|2002|p=35|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Telegraph&quot;&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1338606/Aaliyah.html|title=Aaliyah|date=November 22, 2001|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|accessdate=May 10, 2009 | location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt; Hankerson later introduced her to recording artist and producer [[R. Kelly]],&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt; who became Aaliyah's mentor, as well as lead [[songwriter]] and producer of the album, which was recorded when she was 14.&lt;ref name=&quot;Allmusic&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Telegraph&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Latest Victim&quot;&gt;{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_1_57/ai_79515051/|title=Aaliyah: Latest Victim of Crashes That Cut Short Fame – Obituary|date=November 2001|work=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]|publisher=[[FindArticles]]|accessdate=May 10, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Released in June 1994, the album peaked at number 18 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and sold over three million copies in the United States.&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah albums&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/aaliyah/chart-history/36610?f=305&amp;g=Albums|title=Artist Chart History – Aaliyah – Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media]]|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;SS Music&quot;&gt;{{cite web|title=Aaliyah's Profile|url=http://www.ssmusic.tv/artist_profile.php?Opt=2|publisher=[[SS Music]]|accessdate=July 6, 2010|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070906100607/http://www.ssmusic.tv/artist_profile.php?Opt=2|archivedate=September 6, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah's debut single, &quot;[[Back &amp; Forth (song)|Back &amp; Forth]]&quot;, topped the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&amp;B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart for three weeks and was certified [[music recording sales certification|Gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Billboard&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/chart-beat-bonus-1036092.story|title=Chart Beat Bonus|date=August 31, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;RIAA&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&amp;table=SEARCH_RESULTS&amp;artist=aaliyah&amp;sort=Artist&amp;perPage=25|title=RIAA – Gold &amp; Platinum|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=April 14, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The second single, a [[cover version|cover]] of [[The Isley Brothers]]' &quot;[[At Your Best (You Are Love)]]&quot;, peaked at number six on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and was also certified Gold by the RIAA.&lt;ref name=&quot;Billboard&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;RIAA&quot;/&gt; The title track, &quot;[[Age Ain't Nothing but a Number (song)|Age Ain't Nothing but a Number]]&quot;, peaked at number 75 on the Hot 100.&lt;ref name=&quot;Billboard&quot;/&gt; Additionally, she released &quot;[[The Thing I Like]]&quot; as part of the soundtrack to the 1994 film ''[[A Low Down Dirty Shame]]''.&lt;ref name=&quot;Farley&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Farley|2002|p=103|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===1996–99: ''One in a Million''===
{{Listen|filename=Aaliyah - If Your Girl Only Knew sample.ogg|title=&quot;If Your Girl Only Knew&quot; (1996)|description=The first single released from her second studio album, &quot;[[If Your Girl Only Knew]]&quot; was described as a sassy, organ-infused song.&lt;ref name=&quot;Slant&quot;/&gt; Aaliyah was noted for having &quot;smoother, more seductive, and stronger&quot; singing.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r239065|pure_url=yes}}|title=One in a Million – Overview|last=Stanley|first=Leo|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=June 21, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;|format=[[Ogg]]|pos=right}}
In 1996, Aaliyah left [[Jive Records]] and signed to [[Atlantic Records]].&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt; She worked with record producers [[Timbaland]] and [[Missy Elliott]], who contributed to her second studio album, ''[[One in a Million (Aaliyah album)|One in a Million]]''.&lt;ref name=&quot;AMG rock&quot;/&gt; The album yielded the single &quot;[[If Your Girl Only Knew]]&quot;, which topped the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&amp;B/Hip-Hop Songs]] for two weeks.&lt;ref name=&quot;Billboard&quot;/&gt; It also generated the singles &quot;[[Hot like Fire]]&quot; and &quot;[[4 Page Letter]]&quot;. The following year, Aaliyah was featured on [[Timbaland &amp; Magoo]]'s debut single, &quot;[[Up Jumps da Boogie]]&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Jet&quot;&gt;{{cite journal|date=September 10, 2001|title=Singer Aaliyah, Eight Others Die in Plane Crash in Bahamas|journal=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]|publisher=[[Johnson Publishing Company]]|page=56|issn=0021-5996|url=http://books.google.com/?id=-7QDAAAAMBAJ&amp;pg=PA1|accessdate=June 21, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''One in a Million'' peaked at number 18 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah albums&quot;/&gt; selling over 3.7 million copies in the United States and over eight million copies worldwide.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://musica.univision.com/fotos/slideshow/2010-08-25/aaliyah-a-nueve-anos-de-su-muerte|title=Aaliyah: |last=.|first=.|date=August 25, 2010|work=[[Univision]]|publisher=[[Univision]]|accessdate=September 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Simmonds&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Simmonds|2008|p=454|Ref=Simmonds}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Aaliyah attended the [[Detroit School of Arts|Detroit High School for the Performing Arts]], where she majored in [[drama]] and graduated in 1997 with a 4.0 [[grade (education)|grade point average]].&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/2001-08-25-aaliyah.htm|title=Aaliyah: A life in the spotlight, lost far too early|last=Jones|first=Steve|date=August 28, 2001|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=June 11, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Farley|2002|p=77|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah began her acting career that same year; she played herself in the [[police procedural|police drama]] television series ''[[New York Undercover]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=79|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; During this time, Aaliyah participated in the Children's Benefit Concert, a [[benefit concert|charity concert]] that took place at the [[Beacon Theatre (New York City)|Beacon Theatre]] in New York.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=128|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; She contributed on the soundtrack album for the [[Fox Animation Studios]] animated feature ''[[Anastasia (1997 movie)|Anastasia]]'', performing a [[cover version]] of &quot;[[Journey to the Past]]&quot; which earned songwriters [[Lynn Ahrens]] and [[Stephen Flaherty]] a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Farley&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Simmonds&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/55317.stm|title=Academy Award nominations in full|date=February 10, 1998|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=September 8, 2009|location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah performed the song at the [[70th Academy Awards|1998 Academy Awards ceremony]] and became the youngest singer to perform at the event.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_13_100/ai_78545740/|title=Singer Aaliyah, Eight Others Die in Plane Crash in Bahamas|date=September 10, 2001|work=Jet|publisher=FindArticles|accessdate=May 10, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Remembering Aaliyah|url=http://www.bet.com/Music/photos/msc_photos_RememberingAaliyah.htm?i=6|publisher=[[Black Entertainment Television]]|accessdate=August 26, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Later on that year Tommy Hilfiger gave her an endorsement deal, part of her deal was to model at various Tommy Hilfiger shows. Aaliyah's song Are You That Somebody? was featured on the Dr.Dolittle soundtrack. &quot;Are You That Somebody?&quot; was in the midst of its chart run when Billboard changed its policy to allow airplay-only singles to chart on the Hot 100 and Hot R&amp;B/Hip-Hop charts. It climbed to number four on the Hot 100 Airplay chart and number one on the Hot R&amp;B/Hip-Hop Airplay chart. The single peaked at number 21 on the Billboard Hot 100.

===2000–01: ''Romeo Must Die'' and eponymous album===
In 2000, Aaliyah landed her first major movie role in ''[[Romeo Must Die]]''. A loose adaptation of [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'', Aaliyah starred opposite martial artist [[Jet Li]], playing a couple who fall in love amid their warring families. It grossed [[United States dollar|$]]18.6 million in its first weekend, ranking number two at the box office.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,85088,00.html|title='Romeo' and Julia |last=Wolk|first=Josh|date=March 26, 2000|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|accessdate=May 10, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; In addition to acting, Aaliyah served as an executive producer of the [[Romeo Must Die (soundtrack)|film soundtrack]], where she contributed four songs.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/27/arts/aaliyah-22-singer-who-first-hit-the-charts-at-14.html|title=Aaliyah, 22, Singer Who First Hit the Charts at 14|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=August 27, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=May 10, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; &quot;[[Try Again]]&quot; was released as a single from the soundtrack; the song topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making Aaliyah the first artist to top the chart based solely on [[airplay]]; this led the song to be released in a [[12-inch single|12&quot; vinyl]] and [[gramophone record|7&quot; single]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Billboard&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Bronson|first=Fred|title=The Billboard Book of Number 1 Hits|publisher=Billboard Books|year=2003|page=896|isbn=0-8230-7677-6}}&lt;/ref&gt; The music video won the [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Female Video|Best Female Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Video from a Film|Best Video from a Film]] awards at the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/915759.stm|title=MTV Video Music Awards: The winners|date=September 8, 2000|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=May 21, 2009|location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt; It also earned her a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for Best Female R&amp;B Vocalist.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1510034.stm|title=R&amp;B's Aaliyah dies in plane crash|date=August 26, 2001|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=May 21, 2009|location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt; The soundtrack went on to sell 1.5 million copies in the United States.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/aaliyah-returns-to-music-963309.story|title=Aaliyah Returns to Music|last=Hall|first=Rashaun|date=July 20, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

After completing ''[[Romeo Must Die]]'', Aaliyah began to work on her second film, ''[[Queen of the Damned (film)|Queen of the Damned]]''. She played the role of an ancient vampire, Queen Akasha, which she described as a &quot;manipulative, crazy, sexual being&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Telegraph&quot;/&gt; She was scheduled to film for the sequels of ''[[The Matrix]]'' as the character [[Zee (The Matrix)|Zee]].&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Matrix recast&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453366/20020411/gaye_nona.jhtml|title=Aaliyah's 'Matrix' Role to Be Given to Nona Gaye|last=Goodman|first=Abbey|date=April 11, 2002|publisher=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=April 14, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah went on to release her eponymous album, ''[[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]'', in July 2001. Produced by [[Timbaland]],&lt;ref name=&quot;Allmusic&quot;/&gt; the album debuted at number two on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 187,000 copies in its first week.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/keys-wards-off-aaliyah-foxy-at-no-1-968867.story|title=Keys Wards Off Aaliyah, Foxy at No. 1|last=Martens|first=Todd|date=July 26, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The first single from the album, &quot;[[We Need a Resolution]]&quot;, peaked at number 59 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Billboard&quot;/&gt;

==Musical style and image==
{{Listen|filename=Aaliyah - More Than a Woman sample.ogg|title=&quot;More Than a Woman&quot; (2001)|description=As her albums progressed, [[music critic]]s felt that Aaliyah had matured, noting a &quot;near-flawless declaration of strength and independence&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Farley p6&quot;/&gt;|format=[[Ogg]]|pos=right}}
Aaliyah had a [[vocal range]] of a [[soprano]].&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt; With the release of her debut single &quot;[[Back &amp; Forth (song)|Back &amp; Forth]]&quot;, Dimitri Ehrlich of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' expressed that Aaliyah's &quot;silky vocals are more agile than those of self-proclaimed queen of hip-hop soul [[Mary J. Blige]].&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,302670,00.html|title=Age Ain't Nothing but a Number – Music Review|last=Ehrlich|first=Dimitri|date=June 17, 1994|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah described her sound as &quot;street but sweet&quot;, which featured her &quot;gentle&quot; vocals over a &quot;hard&quot; [[beat (music)|beat]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,168489,00.html|title=Street But Sweet|last=Farley|first=Christopher John|date=July 22, 2001|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=Time|accessdate=May 21, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Though Aaliyah did not write any of her own material,&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt; her lyrics were described as in-depth.&lt;ref name=&quot;SM&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/aaliyah-age-aint-nothing-but-a-number/414|title=Slant Magazine Music Review: Aaliyah: Age Ain't Nothing But A Number|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|year=2001|publisher=Slant|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;eponymous&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/aaliyah-r539210|title=Aaliyah – Aaliyah|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=January 7, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; She incorporated [[contemporary R&amp;B|R&amp;B]], [[pop music|pop]] and [[hip hop music|hip hop]] into her music.&lt;ref name=&quot;AMG rock&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=168|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; Her songs were often uptempo and [[melancholia|melancholy]], revolving around &quot;matters of the heart&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah review&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,168502~4~~aaliyah,00.html|title=Aaliyah – Music Review|last=Seymour|first=Craig|date=June 23, 2001|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Her songs have been said to have &quot;crisp production&quot; and &quot;staccato arrangements&quot; that &quot;extend genre boundaries&quot; while containing &quot;old-school&quot; [[soul music]]. When she experimented with other genres, such as [[Latin pop]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]], writers panned the attempt.&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah review&quot;/&gt; As her albums progressed, writers felt that Aaliyah matured, calling her progress a &quot;declaration of strength and independence&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Farley p6&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Farley|2002|p=6|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;eponymous&quot;/&gt; [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of Allmusic described her eponymous album, ''[[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]'', as &quot;a statement of maturity and a stunning artistic leap forward&quot; and called it one of the strongest urban soul records of its time.&lt;ref name=&quot;eponymous&quot;/&gt; She portrayed &quot;unfamiliar sounds, styles and emotions&quot;, but managed to please critics with the contemporary sound it contained.&lt;ref name=&quot;eponymous&quot;/&gt; Ernest Hardy of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' felt that Aaliyah reflected a stronger technique, where she gave her best vocal performance.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/123191/review/6067616/aaliyah|title=Aaliyah – Aaliyah – Review|last=Hardy|first=Ernest|date=August 2, 2001|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media|accessdate=October 29, 2010|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071224154411/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/123191/review/6067616/aaliyah|archivedate=December 24, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; Others felt that she was &quot;satisfying rather than extraordinary&quot;, stating that she added little to modern R&amp;B.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/aaliyah/5400|title=Aaliyah – Aaliyah – Album  Reviews|last=Mulvey |first=John|date=July 11, 2001|work=[[NME]]|publisher=Time|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-aaliyah-677489.html|title= Album: Aaliyah – Reviews, Music|date=July 13, 2001|work=The Independent|publisher=Independent News &amp; Media|accessdate=April 5, 2009 | location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt;

As an artist, Aaliyah often voiced that she was inspired by a number of performers. These include [[Michael Jackson]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Sade Adu|Sade]], [[En Vogue]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[Korn]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Naughty by Nature]], [[Johnny Mathis]] and [[Janet Jackson]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|pp=8–10|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah expressed that Michael Jackson's ''[[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]'' was her &quot;favorite album&quot; and that &quot;nothing will ever top ''Thriller''.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah&quot;/&gt; She stated that she admired Sade because &quot;she stays true to her style no matter what... she's an amazing artist, an amazing performer... and I absolutely love her.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah&quot;/&gt; Aaliyah expressed she had always desired to work with Janet Jackson—whom she had drawn frequent comparison to over the course of her career, stating &quot;I admire her a great deal. She's a total performer... I'd love to do a duet with Janet Jackson.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|last1=Drennen|first1=Eileen M.|last2=Murray|first2=Sonia|last3=Hamilton|first3=Doug|last4=Dollar|first4=Steve|last5=Henry|first5=Derrick|last6= Janich|first6=Kathy|last7=DeVault|first7=Russ|title=Home Entertainment The Latest In Music, Videos And Books New Music Mini Reviews Review|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]]|date=August 9, 1996|page=G.06|quote=Actually, she's a streetwise Jackson with a far more soulful song selection. The gritty beats just don't stop on 'One in a Million,' which, a la Jackson, has one track after another aching for sensual choreography.}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|last=Johnson|first=Connie|title= Aaliyah's Spirit Sounds Like a 'Million'|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=September 28, 1996|page=8|issn=04583035|quote=Kelly, who produced Aaliyah's 1994 hits 'Back and Forth' and 'At Your Best (You Are Love),' took a girl with admittedly thin vocal chops—but a truckload of poise and precocity—and turned her into the most convincing studio-produced marvel this side of 'Control'-era Janet Jackson.}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|last=Wiltz|first=Teresa|title=Aaliyah's Peek Performance|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=July 22, 2001|page=G.02|issn=01908286|quote=Aaliyah is a contemporary of those other barely post-adolescent R&amp;B crooners, from Mya to Monica to Brandy et al. But with her edge and attitude—not to mention dance skills—the 21-year-old actually has more in common with Janet Jackson.}}&lt;/ref&gt; Jackson reciprocated Aaliyah's affections, commenting &quot;I've loved her from the beginning because she always comes out and does something different, musically.&quot; Jackson also stated she would have enjoyed collaborating with Aaliyah.&lt;ref name=&quot;Aaliyah&quot;/&gt;

Aaliyah focused on her public image throughout her career. She often wore baggy clothes and sunglasses, stating that she wanted to be herself.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=51|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; She described her image as being &quot;important… to differentiate yourself from the rest of the pack&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=52|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; She often wore black clothing, starting a trend for similar fashion among women in United States and Japan.&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Sutherland&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=53|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah participated in fashion designer [[Tommy Hilfiger]]'s All America Tour and was featured in Tommy Jean ads, which depicted her in [[boxer shorts]], baggy jeans and a [[tube top]]. Hilfiger's brother, [[Andy Hilfiger|Andy]], called it &quot;a whole new look&quot; that was &quot;classy but sexy&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Sutherland&quot;/&gt; When she changed her hairstyle, Aaliyah took her mother's advice to cover her left eye, much like [[Veronica Lake]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=54|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1998, she hired a [[personal trainer]] to keep in shape, and exercised five days a week and ate [[diet food]]s.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=50|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah was praised for her &quot;clean-cut image&quot; and &quot;moral values&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/08/26/death.aaliyah/|title=U.S. investigators to probe Aaliyah crash|date=August 27, 2001|publisher=CNN|accessdate=May 21, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Personal life==
With the release of ''[[Age Ain't Nothing but a Number]]'', rumors circulated of a relationship between Aaliyah and Kelly.&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Kenyatta&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Kenyatta|2002|p=25|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; Shortly after, there was speculation about a secret marriage with the release of &quot;Age Ain't Nothing but a Number&quot; and the adult content that Kelly had written for Aaliyah.&lt;ref name=&quot;Vibe&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/online_exclusives/2008/09/rkelly_day_part3/|title=R. Kelly: Indecent Proposal|date=September 18, 2008|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=Vibe Media Group|accessdate=May 14, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' magazine later revealed a [[marriage certificate]] that listed the couple allegedly married on August 31, 1994, in Sheraton Gateway Suites in [[Rosemont, Illinois]].&lt;ref name=&quot;The Independent&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Vibe&quot;/&gt; Aaliyah, who was 15 at the time, was listed as 18 on the certificate; the illegal marriage was reportedly annulled in February 1995 by her parents.&lt;ref name=&quot;Latest Victim&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Vibe&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Story?id=4174733|title=Gone Before 30: Stars Who Died Young|last=Anees|first=Saira|coauthors=Kramer, Carolyn|date=January 29, 2008|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=September 14, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The pair continued to deny marriage allegations, stating that neither was married.&lt;ref name=&quot;Kenyatta&quot;/&gt;

==Death, funeral and wrongful death lawsuit==
On August 25, 2001, at 6:45 pm ([[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]), Aaliyah and various members of the record company boarded a twin-engine [[Cessna 402|Cessna 402B]] ([[Aircraft registration|registration]] N8097W) at [[Marsh Harbour]], [[Abaco Islands]], [[The Bahamas]], to travel to the [[Opa-locka Airport|airport]] in [[Opa-locka, Florida]], after they completed filming the music video for the single [[Rock the Boat (Aaliyah song)|&quot;Rock the Boat&quot;]].&lt;ref name=&quot;MTV News&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1448402/20010826/aaliyah.jhtml|title=Aaliyah Killed in Plane Crash|last=Schumacher-Rasmussen|first=Eric|date=August 26, 2001|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=April 9, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; They had a flight scheduled the following day, but with filming finishing early, Aaliyah and her entourage were eager to return to the United States and made the decision to leave immediately. The designated airplane was smaller than the [[Cessna 404]] on which they had originally flown in. Nevertheless, the whole party and all of the equipment were accommodated on board.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=119|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; As a result, when the aircraft attempted to depart, it was over its maximum takeoff weight by {{convert|700|lb|kg|-1}} and was carrying one more passenger than it was certified to.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1456119/20020716/aaliyah.jhtml|title=Cocaine, Alcohol Found In Pilot Of Aaliyah's Plane|last=Moss|first=Corey|date=July 16, 2002|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=June 17, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The plane crashed shortly after takeoff, about {{convert|200|ft|m|-1}} from the runway.&lt;ref name=&quot;MTV News&quot;/&gt; Aaliyah and the eight others on board, pilot Luis Morales III, hair stylist Eric Forman, Anthony Dodd, security guard Scott Gallin, video producer Douglas Kratz, stylist Christopher Maldonado, and [[Blackground Records]] employees Keith Wallace and Gina Smith, were all killed.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/08/26/death.aaliyah/|title=U.S. investigators to probe Aaliyah crash|date=August 27, 2001|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 8, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

According to findings from an inquest, conducted by the coroner's office in The Bahamas, Aaliyah suffered from &quot;severe burns and a blow to the head&quot;, in addition to severe shock and a weak heart.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/aaliyah/15575|title=Coroner Delivers Verdict Over Aaliyah Death Crash|date=November 20, 2003|publisher=NME|accessdate=March 5, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The coroner theorized that, even if Aaliyah had survived the crash, her recovery would have been virtually impossible given the severity of her injuries.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2003/11/21/aaliyah.htm|title=Bahamas Coroner delivers verdict in Aaliyah death crash|date=November 21, 2003|work=Caribbean News|publisher=Caribbean Net News|accessdate=February 7, 2007|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20040127093955/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2003/11/21/aaliyah.htm|archivedate=January 27, 2004}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) report stated that &quot;the airplane was seen lifting off the runway, and then nose down, impacting in a marsh on the south side of the departure end of runway 27.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;NTSB&quot;&gt;{{cite report|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/ntsb/brief2.asp?ev_id=20010907X01905&amp;ntsbno=MIA01RA225&amp;akey=1|title=NTSB Identification: MIA01RA225|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|accessdate=June 11, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; It also indicated that the pilot was not approved to pilot the plane he was attempting to fly. Morales falsely obtained his [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) license by showing hundreds of hours never flown, and he may also have falsified how many hours he had flown in order to get a job with his employer, Blackhawk International Airways.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Simmonds|2008|p=455|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; Additionally, an [[autopsy]] performed on Morales revealed traces of [[cocaine]] and [[alcohol]] in his system.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/11/19/entertainment/main584494.shtml|title=Aaliyah Crash Pilot Was On Cocaine|last=Holguin|first=Jaime|date=November 11, 2003|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=April 7, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The NTSB reported that the maximum allowed gross weight of the plane was &quot;substantially exceeded&quot; and that the center of gravity was positioned beyond its rear limit.&lt;ref name=&quot;NTSB&quot;/&gt; John Frank of the Cessna Pilots Association stated that the plane was &quot;definitely overloaded&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1448577/20010831/aaliyah.jhtml|title=Report Shows Aaliyah's Plane Was Overloaded|last=Schumacher-Rasmussen|first=Eric|date=August 31, 2001|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; 

[[File:Ferncliff Cemetery Westchester County, New York.jpg|left|thumb|alt=An open gate revealing the road to enter a cemetery, surrounded by grass, flowers and trees.|The entrance to [[Ferncliff Cemetery]], where Aaliyah is interred in a crypt]]

Aaliyah's funeral was held on August 31, 2001, at the Saint Ignatius Loyola Church in [[New York]]. Her body was set in a silver [[casket]], which was carried in a glass [[hearse]] and was drawn by horse.&lt;ref name=&quot;funeral&quot;&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2001/08/26/entertainment/main308179.shtml|title=Hundreds Say Good-Bye to Aaliyah|first=August 31, 2001|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=February 2, 2010 | date=August 26, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt; An estimated 800&amp;nbsp;mourners were in attendance of the procession.&lt;ref name=&quot;Latest Victim&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2001/08/26/entertainment/main308179.shtml|title=Hundreds Say Good-Bye To Aaliyah|last=Miliano|first=Lou|date=August 31, 2001|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=April 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Among those in attendance to the private ceremony were [[Missy Elliott]], [[Timbaland]], [[Gladys Knight]], [[Lil' Kim]] and [[Sean Combs]].&lt;!--This is just a summary of attendees, not an exhaustive guest list. Please reach agreement with other edits on the talk page before inserting any further names.--&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;funeral&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last=Lopez|first=Molly|date=January 25, 2008|title=Frank E. Campbell's Service to the Stars|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20173693,00.html|work=People|publisher=Time|accessdate=August 8, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=In Pictures: Adieu to Aaliyah|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1519692.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=August 8, 2010|date=August 31, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt; After the service, 22 white [[columbidae|doves]] were released to symbolize each year of Aaliyah's life.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1448581/20010831/aaliyah.jhtml|title=Fans, Artists Pay Last Respects To Aaliyah|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=August 31, 2001|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=June 17, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; She was interred in a crypt in a private room in the Rosewood Mausoleum at the [[Ferncliff Cemetery]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,622609,00.html|title=Friday: Funeral, Memorial for Aaliyah|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M.|date=August 31, 2001|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=Time|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The day of the crash was Morales' first official day with Blackhawk International Airways, an FAA Part 135 single-pilot operation. In addition, Morales was not registered with the FAA to fly for Blackhawk. As a result of the accident, a [[wrongful death claim|wrongful death]] lawsuit was filed by Aaliyah's parents and was later settled out of court for an undisclosed amount.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,624572,00.html|title=Aaliyah Remembered One Year Later|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M.|date=August 26, 2002|work=People|publisher=Time|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Barry &amp; Sons, Inc., a corporation formed in 1992 to develop, promote and capitalize Aaliyah and to oversee the production and distribution of her records and music videos, brought an unsuccessful lawsuit in the [[New York Supreme Court]] against Instinct Productions LLC, the company that was hired in August 2001 to produce the music video for &quot;Rock the Boat&quot;. The case was dismissed due to New York's wrongful death statute only permitting certain people to recover damages for wrongful death.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1495396/20050107/aaliyah.jhtml|title=Aaliyah's Label Can't Sue Video Producer Who Booked Ill-Fated Flight|last=Rashbaum|first=Alyssa|date=January 7, 2005|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=June 17, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite report|url=http://www.courts.state.ny.us/reporter/3dseries/2005/2005_00096.htm|title=Barry &amp; Sons, Inc. v Instinct Prods. LLC|last=Sullivan|first=J.|date=January 6, 2005|publisher=New York State Law Reporting Bureau|accessdate=June 11, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Aftermath and posthumous recognition===
The week after Aaliyah's death, her third studio album, ''[[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]'', rose from number 19 to number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/aaliyah-posthumously-tops-album-chart-1046803.story|title=Aaliyah Posthumously Tops Album Chart|last=Martens|first=Todd|date=September 6, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; &quot;[[Rock the Boat (Aaliyah song)|Rock the Boat]]&quot; was released as a posthumous single. The [[music video]] premiered on [[Black Entertainment Television]]'s ''[[Access Granted]]''; it became the most viewed and highest rated episode in the history of the show.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/blogs/2009/08/25/complexs-wifey-hall-of-fame-aaliyah/|title=Complex's Wifey Hall of Fame: Aaliyah|date=August 25, 2009|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|publisher=Complex Media Network|accessdate=August 28, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The song peaked at number 14 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and number two on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&amp;B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart.&lt;ref name=&quot;singles chart&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p44722|pure_url=yes}}|title=Aaliyah = Charts &amp; Awards|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; It was also included on the ''[[Now That's What I Call Music! 8 (U.S. series)|Now That's What I Call Music! 8]]'' compilation series; a portion of the album's profits was donated to the Aaliyah Memorial Fund.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/now-8-dedicated-to-aaliyah-1108342.story|title='NOW! 8' Dedicated to Aaliyah|last=Jeckell|first=Barry A.|date=November 16, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The following two singles from ''Aaliyah'', &quot;[[More than a Woman (Aaliyah song)|More than a Woman]]&quot; and &quot;[[I Care 4 U (song)|I Care 4 U]]&quot;, peaked within the top 25 of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.&lt;ref name=&quot;singles chart&quot;/&gt; The album was certified double [[music recording sales certification|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] and sold 2.6 million copies in the United States.&lt;ref name=&quot;RIAA&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=The Decade in Music: Top 50 Moments|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/the-decade-in-music-top-50-moments-1004055326.story#/news/the-decade-in-music-top-50-moments-page-1004055327.story|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=January 7, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; &quot;More than a Woman&quot; reached number one in the UK singles chart making Aaliyah the first deceased artist to reach number one in the UK single chart, with their first UK release. The song &quot;More than a Woman&quot; was replaced by George Harrison's My Sweet Lord which is the only time in the UK singles chart history where a dead artist has replaced another dead artist at number one.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1758494.stm|title=Posthumous number one for Aaliyah
|source= BBC News|date= January 13, 2001|publisher=BBC|accessdate=April 7, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;
She won two posthumous awards at the [[American Music Awards of 2002]]; Favorite Female R&amp;B Artist and Favorite R&amp;B/Soul Album for ''Aaliyah''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1451722/20020110/keys_alicia.jhtml|title=Alicia Keys, Destiny's Child, Aaliyah Excel At AMAs|last=D'Angelo|first=Joe|date=January 10, 2002|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=April 9, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Her second and final film, ''[[Queen of the Damned (film)|Queen of the Damned]]'', was released in February 2002. Before its release, Aaliyah's brother, Rashad, [[dubbing (filmmaking)|re-dubbed]] some of her lines during post-production.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,623745,00.html|title=Nona Gaye to Fill in for Aaliyah|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M.|date=April 11, 2002|work=People|publisher=Time|accessdate=May 16, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,201771,00.html|title=Movie Preview – Queen of the Damned|date=February 8, 2002|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time|accessdate=May 16, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; It grossed [[United States dollar|$]]15.2 million in its first weekend, ranking number one at the box office.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1839630.stm|title=Aaliyah film tops US box office|date=February 25, 2002|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=May 16, 2009|location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt; On the first anniversary of Aaliyah's death, a candlelight vigil was held in [[Times Square]], where millions of fans observed a [[moment of silence]]. Throughout the United States, radio stations played her music in remembrance.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|date=September 9, 2002|title=Young Legends Who Live On Through Their Music|journal=Jet|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|page=59|issn=0021-5996|url=http://books.google.com/?id=IbYDAAAAMBAJ&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;q|accessdate=August 8, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; In December 2002, a collection of previously unreleased material was released as Aaliyah's first posthumous album, ''[[I Care 4 U]]''. A portion of the proceeds was donated to the Aaliyah Memorial Fund, a program that benefits the Revlon UCLA Women Cancer Research Program and Harlem's Sloan Kettering Cancer Center.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/unreleased-aaliyah-track-hits-the-net-1749813.story|title=Unreleased Aaliyah Track Hits The Net|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=October 28, 2002|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=April 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; It debuted at number three on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 280,000 copies in its first week.&lt;ref name=&quot;IC4U&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/holiday-sales-keep-shania-up-on-top-1780686.story|title=Holiday Sales Keep Shania 'Up' On Top|last=Martens|first=Todd|date=December 18, 2002|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The album's lead single, &quot;[[Miss You (Aaliyah song)|Miss You]]&quot;, peaked at number three on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and topped the [[Hot R&amp;B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart.&lt;ref name=&quot;singles chart&quot;/&gt; In August of the following year, clothing retailer [[Christian Dior SA|Christian Dior]] donated profits from sales in honor of Aaliyah.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/2003-08/030805-aaliyah-honoured-by-dior.aspx?DisplayComments=true|title=Aaliyah Honoured By Dior|date=2003-08-05|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[Condé Nast Publications]]|accessdate=April 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Aaliyah was signed to appear in several future films, including ''[[Honey (2003 film)|Honey]]'' (recast to [[Jessica Alba]]).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|date=July 2008|title=Honey (2003)|journal=[[Torque (magazine)|Torque]]|publisher=SPH Magazines|page=103|issn=0218-7868|url=http://books.google.com/?id=VPcDAAAAMBAJ&amp;pg=PA103|accessdate=June 21, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''Some Kind of Blue'' and a [[Whitney Houston]]-produced remake of the 1976 film ''[[Sparkle (1976 film)|Sparkle]]'' were canceled due to Aaliyah's death.&lt;ref name=&quot;CNN&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,172512,00.html|title=Music News – Obituary|last=Bautz|first=Mark|date=August 26, 2001|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time|accessdate=May 6, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Before her death, Aaliyah had filmed part of her role in ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' and was scheduled to appear in ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'' as [[Zee (The Matrix)|Zee]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Jet&quot;/&gt; The role was later recast to [[Nona Gaye]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Matrix recast&quot;/&gt; Aaliyah's scenes were later included in the tribute section of the ''Matrix Ultimate Collection'' series.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=101|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2005, Aaliyah's second compilation album, ''[[Ultimate Aaliyah]]'' was released in the UK by Blackground Records.&lt;ref name=&quot;Ultimate&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r743273|pure_url=yes}}|title=Ultimate Aaliyah Overview|last=Kellman|first=Andy|year=2005|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=June 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''Ultimate Aaliyah'' is a three disc set, which included a greatest hits audio CD and a DVD.&lt;ref name=&quot;Ultimate&quot;/&gt; Andy Kellman of [[Allmusic]] remarked &quot;''Ultimate Aaliyah'' adequately represents the shortened career of a tremendous talent who benefited from some of the best songwriting and production work by Timbaland, Missy Elliott, and R. Kelly.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;Ultimate&quot;/&gt;

==Legacy==
Aaliyah has been credited for helping redefine [[contemporary R&amp;B|R&amp;B]] and [[hip hop music|hip hop]] in the 1990s, &quot;leaving an indelible imprint on the music industry as a whole.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;SM&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/features/aaliyah.asp|title=Aaliyah (1979–2001)|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|coauthors=Gonzalez, Ed|publisher=Slant|accessdate=May 10, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Steve Huey of Allmusic wrote Aaliyah ranks among the &quot;elite&quot; artists of the R&amp;B genre, as she &quot;played a major role in popularizing the stuttering, futuristic production style that consumed hip-hop and urban soul in the late '90s.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p44722|pure_url=yes}}|title=Aaliyah: Biography|last=Huey|first=Steve|year=2009|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=June 22, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Described as one of &quot;R&amp;B's most important artists&quot; during the 1990s,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r620051|pure_url=yes}}|title=I Care 4 U – Overview|last=Bush|first=John|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; her second studio album, ''[[One in a Million (Aaliyah album)|One in a Million]]'', became one of the most influential R&amp;B albums of the decade.&lt;ref name=&quot;Slant&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/aaliyah-one-in-a-million/415|title=Aaliyah: One in a Million|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|year=2001|publisher=[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]|accessdate=January 3, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; According to Sal Cinquemani of [[Slant Magazine]], Aaliyah provided a &quot;missing link&quot; between hip hop and [[electronica]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/aaliyah-aaliyah/1|title=Aaliyah: Aaliyah – Music Review|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=July 17, 2001|publisher=Slant|accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; With sales of 8.1 million albums in the United States and an estimated 24 to 32 million albums worldwide,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/ask-billboard-titanic-mid-90s-singers-tori-1003921966.story#/news/ask-billboard-titanic-mid-90s-singers-tori-1003921966.story|title=Ask Billboard: 'Titanic,' Mid-'90s Singers, Tori Amos|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=December 12, 2008|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=October 18, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=January 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Eliot|first=Marc|title=Song of Brooklyn: An Oral History of America's Favorite Borough|publisher=[[Random House]]|year=2008|page=38|isbn=0-7679-2014-7}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|date=December 18, 2008|title=Canadian R&amp;B Singer Selected to Play Aaliyah in Biopic|url=http://www.bet.com/News/news_canadiansingertoplayaaliysh.htm?wbc_purpose=Basic&amp;WBCMODE=PresentationUnpublished&amp;Referrer={3F0AAD73-23CB-422F-8297-63E813988FAD}|publisher=Black Entertainment Television|accessdate=July 6, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah has been named the &quot;[[honorific nicknames in popular music|Princess of R&amp;B]]&quot; and  &quot;[[honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen Of Urban Pop]]&quot; &lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=21|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;http://www.vh1.com/shows/behind_the_music/episode.jhtml?episodeID=54581&lt;/ref&gt; and &quot;proved she was a muse in her own right&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,396798,00.html|title=I Care 4 U|last=Seymour|first=Craig|date=December 13, 2002|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time|accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Ernest Hardy of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' dubbed her as the &quot;undisputed queen of the midtempo come-on&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Telegraph&quot;/&gt;  

Aaliyah was honored at the [[2001 MTV Video Music Awards]] by [[Janet Jackson]], [[Missy Elliott]], [[Timbaland]], [[Ginuwine]] and her brother, Rashad, who all paid tribute to her.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1448717/20010906/aaliyah.jhtml|title=Janet, Missy, Others Honor Aaliyah During VMAs|last=D'Angelo|first=Joe|date=September 6, 2001|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=June 17, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the same year, the United States [[Social Security Administration]] ranked the name Aaliyah one of the 100 most popular names for newborn girls.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Brackett|first=Nathan|coauthors=Hoard, Christian David|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide: Completely Revised and Updated 4th Edition|publisher=[[Simon &amp; Schuster]]|year=2004|page=1|isbn=0-7432-0169-8}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaliyah was ranked as one of &quot;The Top 40 Women of the Video Era&quot; and &quot;100 Sexiest Artists&quot; in [[VH1]]'s 2003 ''The Greatest'' series.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=66355|title=The Greatest – Ep. 71 '50 Greatest Women of the Video Era'|publisher=[[VH1]]|accessdate=June 15, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://prnewswire.vn/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&amp;STORY=/www/story/09-19-2002/0001803079|title=Madonna Tops the List as VH1 Counts Down Music's '100 Sexiest Artists' In Five-Hour, Five Night Special, Premiering September 23–27 at 10:00 P.M. (ET/PT)|date=September 19, 2003|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|accessdate=June 15, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; She was also ranked at number 18 on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET's]] &quot;Top 25 Dancers of All Time&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/OnTV/BETShows/top25dancers.htm|title=Top 25 Dancers|date=February 1, 2008|publisher=Black Entertainment Television|accessdate=June 15, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; In memory of Aaliyah, the [[Entertainment Industry Foundation]] created the Aaliyah Memorial Fund to donate money raised to charities she supported.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/2003-08-04-aaliyah_x.htm|title=Celebs party in Aaliyah's honor |last=Endrst|first=James|date=August 4, 2003|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|accessdate=June 17, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sutherland|2005|p=205|Ref=none}}&lt;/ref&gt; In December 2009, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine ranked Aaliyah at number 70 on its Top Artists of the Decade,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts-decade-end/artists-of-the-decade?year=2009&amp;begin=61&amp;order=position|title=Best of the 2000s – Artists of the Decade|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=May 11, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; while her [[Aaliyah (album)|eponymous album]] was ranked at number 181 on the magazine's Top 200 Albums of the Decade.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts-decade-end/billboard-200-albums?year=2009&amp;begin=181&amp;order=position|title=Best of the 2000s – Billboard 200 Albums|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

