==Managers==
{{Main|List of Arsenal F.C. managers}}
There have been eighteen permanent and five [[caretaker manager]]s of Arsenal since the appointment of the club's first professional manager, [[Thomas Mitchell (football manager)|Thomas Mitchell]] in 1897.&lt;ref name=&quot;soar&quot;&gt;{{cite book | last=Soar &amp; Tyler | title=The Official Illustrated History of Arsenal | year=2005 | page=30 }}&lt;/ref&gt; The club's longest-serving manager as of 2009, in terms of both length of tenure and number of games overseen, is [[Arsène Wenger]], who was appointed in 1996.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8286929.stm |title=Wenger hungry for further success |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 October 2009 |accessdate=6 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;700 not out&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1092959/700-Arsenal-boss-Wenger-looking-celebrate-memorable-day-Porto.html |title=700 and not out: Arsenal boss Wenger looking to celebrate memorable day at Porto |first=Christopher |last=Davies |work=Mail Online|date=8 December 2008 |accessdate=6 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Wenger is also Arsenal's only manager from outside the United Kingdom.&lt;ref name=&quot;700 not out&quot;/&gt; Two Arsenal managers have died in the job&amp;nbsp;– [[Herbert Chapman]] and [[Tom Whittaker (footballer)|Tom Whittaker]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.arsenal.com/history/the-managers | title=The Managers | publisher=Arsenal F.C | accessdate=7 September 2008 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Honours==
{{details|Arsenal F.C. seasons}}
{{See also|Arsenal F.C. Reserves#Honours|Arsenal F.C. Academy#Honours}}

===Domestic===
*'''[[Football League First Division|First Division]]''' (until 1992) and '''[[Premier League]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;divisions&quot;&gt;Up until 1992, the top division of [[Football in England|English football]] was the [[Football League First Division]]; since then, it has been the [[Premier League]]. Similarly until 1992, the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] was the second tier of league football, which since the 2004–05 season has been known as [[Football League Championship|The Championship]].&lt;/ref&gt;
:'''Winners (13)''': [[1930–31 in English football|1930–31]], [[1932–33 in English football|1932–33]], [[1933–34 in English football|1933–34]], [[1934–35 in English football|1934–35]], [[1937–38 in English football|1937–38]], [[1947–48 in English football|1947–48]], [[1952–53 in English football|1952–53]], [[1970–71 in English football|1970–71]], [[1988–89 in English football|1988–89]], [[1990–91 in English football|1990–91]], [[1997–98 FA Premier League|1997–98]], [[2001–02 FA Premier League|2001–02]], [[2003–04 FA Premier League|2003–04]]
:Runners-up (8): [[1925–26 in English football|1925–26]], [[1931–32 in English football|1931–32]], [[1972–73 in English football|1972–73]], [[1998–99 FA Premier League|1998–99]], [[1999–2000 FA Premier League|1999–2000]], [[2000–01 FA Premier League|2000–01]], [[2002-03 FA Premier League|2002–03]], [[2004–05 FA Premier League|2004–05]]

* '''[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;divisions&quot;/&gt;
:Runners-up (1): [[1903–04 in English football|1903–04]]

* '''[[FA Cup]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;
:'''Winners (10)''': [[1930 FA Cup Final|1930]], [[1936 FA Cup Final|1936]], [[1950 FA Cup Final|1950]], [[1971 FA Cup Final|1971]], [[1979 FA Cup Final|1979]], [[1993 FA Cup Final|1993]], [[1998 FA Cup Final|1998]], [[2002 FA Cup Final|2002]], [[2003 FA Cup Final|2003]], [[2005 FA Cup Final|2005]]
:Runners-up (7): [[1927 FA Cup Final|1927]], [[1932 FA Cup Final|1932]], [[1952 FA Cup Final|1952]], [[1972 FA Cup Final|1972]], [[1978 FA Cup Final|1978]], [[1980 FA Cup Final|1980]], [[2001 FA Cup Final|2001]]

* '''[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;
:'''Winners (2)''': [[1987 Football League Cup Final|1987]], [[1993 Football League Cup Final|1993]]
:Runners-up (5): [[1968 Football League Cup Final|1968]], [[1969 Football League Cup Final|1969]], [[1988 Football League Cup Final|1988]], [[2007 Football League Cup Final|2007]], [[2011 Football League Cup Final|2011]]

* '''[[FA Community Shield]]''' ('''FA Charity Shield''' before 2002)&lt;ref&gt;The trophy was known as the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]] until 2001, and as the Community Shield since then. Reference: {{cite web
| url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engsupcuphist.html
| title=England – List of FA Charity/Community Shield Matches
| publisher=RSSSF
| last=Ross |first=James
| date=28 August 2009
| accessdate=12 January 2010

}}&lt;/ref&gt;
:'''Winners (12)''': [[1930 FA Charity Shield|1930]], [[1931 FA Charity Shield|1931]], [[1933 FA Charity Shield|1933]], [[1934 FA Charity Shield|1934]], [[1938 FA Charity Shield|1938]], [[1948 FA Charity Shield|1948]], [[1953 FA Charity Shield|1953]], [[1991 FA Charity Shield|1991]] (shared), [[1998 FA Charity Shield|1998]], [[1999 FA Charity Shield|1999]], [[2002 FA Community Shield|2002]], [[2004 FA Community Shield|2004]]
:Runners-up (7): [[1935 FA Charity Shield|1935]], [[1936 FA Charity Shield|1936]], [[1979 FA Charity Shield|1979]], [[1989 FA Charity Shield|1989]], [[1993 FA Charity Shield|1993]], [[2003 FA Community Shield|2003]], [[2005 FA Community Shield|2005]]
&lt;!--
this section is for competitive honours, not pre-season tournaments or friendly matches
--&gt;

===European===

* '''[[UEFA Champions League]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;
:Runners-up (1): [[2006 UEFA Champions League Final|2006]]

* '''[[Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;
:'''Winners (1)''': [[1994 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final|1994]]
:Runners-up (2): [[1980 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final|1980]], [[1995 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final|1995]]

* '''[[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;
:'''Winners (1)''': [[1970 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup Final|1970]]

* '''[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;
:Runners-up (1): [[2000 UEFA Cup Final|2000]]

* '''[[UEFA Super Cup]]'''&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;
:Runners-up (1): [[1994 UEFA Super Cup|1994]]

Arsenal's tally of thirteen League Championships is the third highest in English football, after [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
| url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engchamp.html#sall
| title=England – List of Champions
| publisher=RSSSF
| last=Ross |first=James M
| date=28 August 2009
| accessdate=23 October 2009

}}&lt;/ref&gt; while the total of ten FA Cups is the second highest, after Manchester United.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
| url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engcuphist.html#sall
| title=England FA Challenge Cup Finals
| publisher=RSSSF
| last=Ross |first=James M
| date=12 June 2009
| accessdate=23 October 2009

}}&lt;/ref&gt; Arsenal have achieved three League and FA Cup &quot;[[The Double|Doubles]]&quot; (in 1971, 1998 and 2002), a record shared with Manchester United,&lt;ref name=FCHD/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
| url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/doublerec.html#coun
| title=Doing the Double: Countrywise Records
| publisher=RSSSF
| last=Stokkermans |first=Karel
| date=24 September 2009
| accessdate=23 October 2009

}}&lt;/ref&gt; and in 1993 were the first side in English football to complete the FA Cup and League Cup double.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2313666/Mourinho-collects-his-consolation-prize.html
| title=Mourinho collects his consolation prize
| first=Roy |last=Collins
| newspaper=The Daily Telegraph
| date=20 May 2007 |accessdate=6 December 2009
| quote=Chelsea's Cup came wrapped in an extra ribbon, only the second team after Arsenal in 1993 to win both domestic cups.

}}&lt;/ref&gt; They were also the first London club to reach the final of the UEFA Champions League, in 2006.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
| url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/arsenal
| title=Arsenal Football Club
| publisher=Premier League
| accessdate=11 August 2008 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Arsenal have one of the best top-flight records in history, having finished below fourteenth only seven times. Arsenal also have the highest average league finishing position for the period 1900–1999, with an average league placing of 8.5.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
| title=How consistency and caution made Arsenal England's greatest team of the 20th century
| url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-how-consistency-and-caution-made-arsenal-englands-greatest-team-of-the-20th-century-1133020.html
| last=Hodgson |first=Guy
| work=The Independent
| date=17 December 1999
| accessdate=23 October 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; &lt;!-- Archive copy available at: {{cite web | title=Arsenal: Team of the Century 1900–1999
| url=http://arseweb.com/99-00/century.html
| work=Arseweb
| accessdate=11 August 2008

}}&lt;/ref&gt; --&gt; In addition, they are one of only six clubs to have won the FA Cup twice in succession, in 2002 and 2003.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
| url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engcuphist.html
| title=England FA Challenge Cup Finals
| publisher=RSSSF
| last=Ross |first=James M
| date=12 June 2009
| accessdate=23 October 2009

}}&lt;/ref&gt;

